Fair enough! I do want to clarify one thing, though  and this might be something that I've simply failed to get across with the text within the skip itself:

The actual reason these people are terrified has very little to with the trees or Cragglewood Park. They're terrified because every time they think of those trees, they're coming close to something they've forgotten: That their siblings took their place.

As flashy as the pictures might be, that was the central horror I wanted to evoke: The horror of realizing somebody you love sacrificed themselves for you  and you can't even remember their name. Maybe I failed to get that across, though (I can be way too subtle about implying these things, sometimes).

ETA:  That being said, rereading it, I can see how  I might be overplaying my hand. I made an edit to ratchet back the fear and have the man treat it more like a dream. This better reflects his particular way of coping with it: He just presumes it was a dream.





